42-year-old male presents after a fall from a 6-foot ladder at 1400, striking the right side of his face on concrete. He has a 4cm complex laceration over the right eyebrow extending to the forehead with visible subcutaneous fat. He also reports hitting the back of his head on the ground, with a brief dazed period lasting approximately 30 seconds — no definite loss of consciousness per coworker witness. He reports mild headache and one episode of nausea.

Vitals: BP 138/82, HR 78, SpO2 99%, temp 98.2. GCS 15. On exam: 4cm stellate laceration right supraorbital region, actively bleeding. Neurological exam grossly intact — pupils equal and reactive, no focal deficits, gait normal. Canadian CT Head Rule assessed — mechanism with fall from height and dangerous mechanism positive. CT head without contrast obtained at 1430 — no acute intracranial pathology, no fracture.

Laceration repair performed: wound irrigated with 500cc NS, explored — no foreign body, periosteum intact. Repaired with 4-0 nylon, 12 interrupted sutures, good cosmetic alignment. Tetanus updated.

Concussion precautions given. Return precautions for worsening headache, vomiting, confusion, or focal weakness. Follow-up with primary care in 2 days. Suture removal in 7-10 days.

Disposition: discharge.
